## II. Spread: How Far the Cloud Extends

Knowing the center is not enough — you also need to know how *spread out* the numbers are. A factory making bolts wants the mean diameter to be 10mm, but it also wants every bolt to be *close* to 10mm. The spread tells you the risk, the uncertainty, the variation.

The simplest measure of spread is the **range** (max minus min). More informative is the **interquartile range** (IQR), which captures the middle 50%. The most widely used measure is the **standard deviation** (SD), which quantifies the typical distance from the mean. The **variance** is the square of the standard deviation; it shows up in formulas, but SD has the same units as the data, so it's easier to interpret.

We have `stat/range`, `stat/iqr`, `stat/sd`, `stat/sd-sample`, `stat/variance`, and `stat/variance-sample` wired. The `-sample` versions use *n−1* in the denominator, giving an unbiased estimate when you're working with a sample rather than the whole population — a subtle but important correction.

### Example 8.6: Range of a dataset

```scheme
(define temps (list 68 72 71 75 70 73 69))
(define r (stat/range temps))
r
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; prints the difference between max and min, 7 -->
