## III. The Shape of Spread: Quartiles and the Five-Number Summary

To see the full shape of a dataset's spread, we use the **five-number summary**: minimum, first quartile (Q1, the 25th percentile), median (Q2, the 50th percentile), third quartile (Q3, the 75th percentile), and maximum. This summary powers the **box plot**, one of the most informative graphics in statistics.

We have `stat/min`, `stat/max`, `stat/median`, and `stat/quartile` wired. Let's build a five-number summary by hand.

### Example 8.12: Five-number summary

```scheme
(define grades (list 58 63 67 70 72 75 78 82 85 88 92 95))
(define summary
  (list
    (stat/min grades)
    (stat/quartile grades 0.25)
    (stat/median grades)
    (stat/quartile grades 0.75)
    (stat/max grades)))
summary
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; prints a list of five numbers: min, Q1, median, Q3, max -->
[VISUAL: text output, the five-number summary as a list]

### Example 8.13: Range vs IQR comparison

```scheme
(define dataset (list 10 12 14 15 16 17 18 20 100))
(define r (stat/range dataset))
(define iqr (stat/iqr dataset))
(list r iqr)
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; prints (90 6) — the range is inflated by the outlier 100, but the IQR is robust -->
[VISUAL: text output, two numbers showing the outlier's effect]

