## IV. Z-Scores: Measuring Unusualness

Once you know the mean and standard deviation of a dataset, you can ask: *how unusual is this particular value?* The **z-score** answers that question by expressing a value as a number of standard deviations away from the mean. A z-score of 0 means \"exactly at the mean.\" A z-score of +2 means \"two standard deviations above the mean\" — which, if the data is roughly bell-shaped, is quite rare (only about 2.5% of values lie above z = +2 in a perfect normal distribution).

The formula is simple:  
**z = (value − mean) / SD**

We have `stat/z-score` wired. Let's use it.

### Example 8.14: A typical z-score

```scheme
(define exam-scores (list 70 75 80 85 90 95))
(define student-score 85)
(define z (stat/z-score exam-scores student-score))
z
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; prints the z-score of 85 in the context of the six scores -->
[VISUAL: text output, the z-score (likely near 0 since 85 is close to the mean)]

### Example 8.15: A z-score for an outlier

```scheme
(define weights (list 150 152 151 149 150 151 180))
(define unusual-weight 180)
(define z-outlier (stat/z-score weights unusual-weight))
z-outlier
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; prints a large positive z-score for the outlier -->
[VISUAL: text output, a z-score well above 2]

### Example 8.16: Negative z-score (below the mean)

```scheme
(define reaction-times (list 220 230 240 250 260))
(define fast-time 220)
(define z-fast (stat/z-score reaction-times fast-time))
z-fast
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; prints a negative z-score for the fastest (lowest) time -->
[VISUAL: text output, a z-score around −1.4]

### Example 8.17: Z-scores for all values in a dataset

Z-scores are often computed for every value in a dataset to *standardize* it — transforming it to mean 0, SD 1. This is a manual map over the list:

```scheme
(define data (list 10 20 30 40 50))
(define m (stat/mean data))
(define s (stat/sd data))
(define z-scores
  (map (lambda (x) (/ (- x m) s)) data))
z-scores
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; prints a list of z-scores, one per original value -->
[VISUAL: text output, a list of five z-scores summing to ~0]

### Example 8.18: Interpreting z-scores (simple threshold)

A common rule: if |z| > 2, the value is \"unusual.\" Let's flag outliers:

```scheme
(define heights (list 160 165 162 158 161 180 159))
(define mean-h (stat/mean heights))
(define sd-h (stat/sd heights))
(define unusual?
  (lambda (h)
    (> (abs (stat/z-score heights h)) 2)))
(filter unusual? heights)
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; prints the list of heights with |z| > 2, likely just (180) -->
[VISUAL: text output, a list containing the outlier(s)]

