## V. Correlation: Do Two Variables Move Together?

Often we measure *pairs* of values on each individual: hours studied and exam score, height and weight, advertising spend and sales. **Correlation** quantifies whether two variables tend to increase together (positive correlation), decrease together (negative correlation), or vary independently (correlation near zero). The **Pearson correlation coefficient** *r* ranges from −1 (perfect negative) to +1 (perfect positive).

The formula involves z-scores of both variables — it's the average product of their z-scores. We don't have a wired `stat/correlation` verb yet, so we'll compute it by hand using wired verbs.

<!-- BUILD: needs verb stat/correlation -->

### Example 8.19: Computing correlation manually (simple dataset)

```scheme
(define xs (list 1 2 3 4 5))
(define ys (list 2 4 5 4 5))

(define mean-x (stat/mean xs))
(define mean-y (stat/mean ys))
(define sd-x (stat/sd xs))
(define sd-y (stat/sd ys))

(define z-products
  (map (lambda (x y)
         (* (/ (- x mean-x) sd-x)
            (/ (- y mean-y) sd-y)))
       xs ys))

(define r (/ (stat/sum z-products) (length xs)))
r
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; prints the Pearson correlation coefficient for the five pairs -->
[VISUAL: text output, a number between −1 and +1, likely positive and moderate]

### Example 8.20: Perfect positive correlation

```scheme
(define xs (list 1 2 3 4 5))
(define ys (list 10 20 30 40 50))

(define mean-x (stat/mean xs))
(define mean-y (stat/mean ys))
(define sd-x (stat/sd xs))
(define sd-y (stat/sd ys))

(define z-products
  (map (lambda (x y)
         (* (/ (- x mean-x) sd-x)
            (/ (- y mean-y) sd-y)))
       xs ys))

(define r (/ (stat/sum z-products) (length xs)))
r
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; prints 1.0 (or very close), since y = 10x exactly -->
[VISUAL: text output, r = 1]

