## VIII. Fitting Through the Origin (Forcing Intercept to Zero)

Sometimes you know on physical grounds that the line should pass through the origin — for example, zero input should give zero output. In that case, you fit **y = mx** (intercept forced to zero). The matrix **A** has only one column (the x-values), and `linalg/least-squares` returns a single coefficient (the slope).

### Example 8.32: Fit y = mx (no intercept)

```scheme
(define xs (list 1 2 3 4 5))
(define ys (list 1.9 4.2 5.8 8.1 10.3))

(define A
  (matrix/make
    (map (lambda (x) (list x)) xs)))

(define y-vec (vec/make 1.9 4.2 5.8 8.1 10.3))

(define coeffs (linalg/least-squares A y-vec))
(define m (vec/ref coeffs 0))

m
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; prints the slope of the best-fit line through the origin -->
[VISUAL: text output, a single number (the slope)]

### Example 8.33: Plot the origin-constrained fit

```scheme
(define xs (list 1 2 3 4 5))
(define ys (list 2.1 3.9 6.0 7.8 10.2))

(define A
  (matrix/make
    (map (lambda (x) (list x)) xs)))

(define y-vec (vec/make 2.1 3.9 6.0 7.8 10.2))

(define coeffs (linalg/least-squares A y-vec))
(define m (vec/ref coeffs 0))

(define fit-fn (lambda (x) (* m x)))

(define points
  (map (lambda (x y) (geom/point x y)) xs ys))

(plot/render-svg
  (plot/with
    (plot/scatter points)
    (plot/function fit-fn 0 6)))
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; renders scatter + line through origin -->
[VISUAL: graphing-calculator surface, Cartesian, line passing through (0,0)]

