## X. Transforming Data for Linear Regression (Log-Linear Fit)

If the relationship between x and y is exponential (**y = a · e^(bx)**), you can *linearize* it by taking the logarithm: **ln(y) = ln(a) + bx**. Fit a line to **(x, ln(y))**, then exponentiate the result to get back the exponential model.

### Example 8.36: Log-transform and fit

```scheme
(define xs (list 0 1 2 3 4))
(define ys (list 2.1 5.5 14.8 40.2 109.0))

(define ln-ys (map math/log ys))

(define A
  (matrix/make
    (map (lambda (x) (list 1 x)) xs)))

(define y-vec
  (vec/make
    (math/log 2.1)
    (math/log 5.5)
    (math/log 14.8)
    (math/log 40.2)
    (math/log 109.0)))

(define coeffs (linalg/least-squares A y-vec))
(define ln-a (vec/ref coeffs 0))
(define b (vec/ref coeffs 1))

(define a (math/exp ln-a))

(list 'a a 'b b)
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; prints the exponential model parameters a and b -->
[VISUAL: text output, two numbers (a and b) for y = a exp(bx)]

### Example 8.37: Plot the exponential fit

```scheme
(define xs (list 0 1 2 3 4))
(define ys (list 2.1 5.5 14.8 40.2 109.0))

(define ln-ys (map math/log ys))

(define A
  (matrix/make
    (map (lambda (x) (list 1 x)) xs)))

(define y-vec
  (vec/make
    (math/log 2.1)
    (math/log 5.5)
    (math/log 14.8)
    (math/log 40.2)
    (math/log 109.0)))

(define coeffs (linalg/least-squares A y-vec))
(define ln-a (vec/ref coeffs 0))
(define b (vec/ref coeffs 1))
(define a (math/exp ln-a))

(define fit-fn
  (lambda (x)
    (* a (math/exp (* b x)))))

(define points
  (map (lambda (x y) (geom/point x y)) xs ys))

(plot/render-svg
  (plot/with
    (plot/scatter points)
    (plot/function fit-fn -0.5 4.5)))
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; renders scatter + exponential curve -->
