## XI. R² (Coefficient of Determination): How Good Is the Fit?

The **R²** statistic measures the fraction of variance in *y* explained by the model. It ranges from 0 (the model explains nothing) to 1 (the model explains everything). The formula:

**R² = 1 − (SSE / SST)**

where **SSE** is the sum of squared residuals (errors), and **SST** is the total sum of squares (variance of y around its mean).

We'll compute it by hand.

### Example 8.38: Compute R² for a linear fit

```scheme
(define xs (list 1 2 3 4 5))
(define ys (list 2.1 4.0 5.9 8.1 9.8))

(define A
  (matrix/make
    (map (lambda (x) (list 1 x)) xs)))

(define y-vec (vec/make 2.1 4.0 5.9 8.1 9.8))

(define coeffs (linalg/least-squares A y-vec))
(define b (vec/ref coeffs 0))
(define m (vec/ref coeffs 1))

(define predict (lambda (x) (+ b (* m x))))

(define residuals
  (map (lambda (x y) (- y (predict x))) xs ys))

(define sse
  (stat/sum (map (lambda (r) (* r r)) residuals)))

(define mean-y (stat/mean ys))

(define total-deviations
  (map (lambda (y) (- y mean-y)) ys))

(define sst
  (stat/sum (map (lambda (d) (* d d)) total-deviations)))

(define r-squared (- 1 (/ sse sst)))

r-squared
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; prints R², a number near 1 if the fit is good -->
[VISUAL: text output, the R² value]

### Example 8.39: R² for a perfect fit

When all points lie exactly on a line, R² = 1:

```scheme
(define xs (list 1 2 3 4 5))
(define ys (list 3 5 7 9 11))

(define A
  (matrix/make
    (map (lambda (x) (list 1 x)) xs)))

(define y-vec (vec/make 3 5 7 9 11))

(define coeffs (linalg/least-squares A y-vec))
(define b (vec/ref coeffs 0))
(define m (vec/ref coeffs 1))

(define predict (lambda (x) (+ b (* m x))))

(define residuals
  (map (lambda (x y) (- y (predict x))) xs ys))

(define sse
  (stat/sum (map (lambda (r) (* r r)) residuals)))

(define mean-y (stat/mean ys))

(define total-deviations
  (map (lambda (y) (- y mean-y)) ys))

(define sst
  (stat/sum (map (lambda (d) (* d d)) total-deviations)))

(define r-squared (- 1 (/ sse sst)))

r-squared
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; prints 1.0 (or very close) -->
[VISUAL: text output, R² = 1]

### Example 8.40: R² for a poor fit (horizontal line model)

When the model is just the mean (no x dependence), R² = 0:

```scheme
(define xs (list 1 2 3 4 5))
(define ys (list 10 2 8 3 7))

(define mean-y (stat/mean ys))

(define predict (lambda (x) mean-y))

(define residuals
  (map (lambda (x y) (- y (predict x))) xs ys))

(define sse
  (stat/sum (map (lambda (r) (* r r)) residuals)))

(define total-deviations
  (map (lambda (y) (- y mean-y)) ys))

(define sst
  (stat/sum (map (lambda (d) (* d d)) total-deviations)))

(define r-squared (- 1 (/ sse sst)))

r-squared
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; prints 0.0 (or very close) -->
[VISUAL: text output, R² ≈ 0]

