## XII. Confidence and Prediction Intervals (Conceptual)

In practice, once you've fitted a line, you want to know: *how uncertain is this estimate?* **Confidence intervals** for the slope and intercept, and **prediction intervals** for a future y-value, quantify that uncertainty. The formulas require the standard error of the regression and the leverage of each x-value — they involve the t-distribution and are staples of introductory statistics courses.

We don't have wired verbs for these intervals yet, but we can sketch the idea: the standard error of the regression is **sqrt(SSE / (n − 2))**, and the standard error of the slope involves that quantity and the spread of the x-values. Let's compute the regression standard error.

<!-- BUILD: needs verbs for confidence/prediction intervals (stat/se-regression, stat/ci-slope, etc.) -->

### Example 8.41: Standard error of the regression

```scheme
(define xs (list 1 2 3 4 5 6))
(define ys (list 2.3 3.7 5.1 6.8 8.2 9.5))

(define A
  (matrix/make
    (map (lambda (x) (list 1 x)) xs)))

(define y-vec (vec/make 2.3 3.7 5.1 6.8 8.2 9.5))

(define coeffs (linalg/least-squares A y-vec))
(define b (vec/ref coeffs 0))
(define m (vec/ref coeffs 1))

(define predict (lambda (x) (+ b (* m x))))

(define residuals
  (map (lambda (x y) (- y (predict x))) xs ys))

(define sse
  (stat/sum (map (lambda (r) (* r r)) residuals)))

(define n (length xs))

(define se-regression
  (math/pow (/ sse (- n 2)) 0.5))

se-regression
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; prints the standard error of the regression -->
[VISUAL: text output, a small positive number quantifying the scatter around the line]

---

## XIII. Weighted Least Squares (Conceptual)

Sometimes points have different *reliability* — one measurement might have a small error bar, another a large one. **Weighted least squares** gives more influence to the reliable points by minimizing a *weighted* sum of squared residuals. The matrix **A** and vector **y** remain the same, but you pre-multiply by a diagonal weight matrix. We don't have a wired `linalg/weighted-least-squares`, but the idea is: multiply each row of **A** and each element of **y** by **sqrt(weight_i)**, then solve the standard least-squares problem.

<!-- BUILD: needs verb linalg/weighted-least-squares or manual weight matrix -->

We'll skip the code here (no wired support), but note that this technique is fundamental in experimental physics and econometrics.

---

## XIV. Interpreting Residuals: Patterns and Diagnostics

After fitting a model, always *look at the residuals*. If the residuals show a pattern (e.g., they increase with x, or they cluster in a U-shape), the linear model is missing something — maybe the relationship is quadratic, or maybe the variance is not constant. **Homoscedasticity** (constant variance) is an assumption of least squares; if it's violated, you might need a transform or a different model.

### Example 8.42: Plot residuals vs x (checking for patterns)

```scheme
(define xs (list 1 2 3 4 5 6))
(define ys (list 2.1 4.3 6.8 9.0 11.5 13.9))

(define A
  (matrix/make
    (map (lambda (x) (list 1 x)) xs)))

(define y-vec (vec/make 2.1 4.3 6.8 9.0 11.5 13.9))

(define coeffs (linalg/least-squares A y-vec))
(define b (vec/ref coeffs 0))
(define m (vec/ref coeffs 1))

(define predict (lambda (x) (+ b (* m x))))

(define residuals
  (map (lambda (x y) (- y (predict x))) xs ys))

(define residual-points
  (map (lambda (x r) (geom/point x r)) xs residuals))

(plot/render-svg
  (plot/scatter residual-points))
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; renders a scatter of (x, residual) — ideally a random cloud around zero -->
[VISUAL: graphing-calculator surface, Cartesian, residuals vs x]

### Example 8.43: Residuals for a quadratic relationship fit with a line (bad fit)

If the true relationship is quadratic and we fit a line, residuals will show a systematic curve:

```scheme
(define xs (list 1 2 3 4 5 6))
(define ys (list 2.0 3.5 6.0 9.5 14.0 19.5))

(define A
