## XV. Multiple Linear Regression (More Than One Predictor)

When you have multiple predictors (say, *x₁* and *x₂*) and want to fit **y = b + m₁x₁ + m₂x₂**, the matrix **A** has three columns: **[1, x₁, x₂]**. `linalg/least-squares` handles this seamlessly — just build the right matrix.

### Example 8.44: Fit y = b + m₁x₁ + m₂x₂

```scheme
(define x1s (list 1 2 3 4 5))
(define x2s (list 2 3 5 7 11))
(define ys (list 3.1 5.9 9.8 13.2 19.7))

(define A
  (matrix/make
    (map (lambda (x1 x2) (list 1 x1 x2))
         x1s x2s)))

(define y-vec (vec/make 3.1 5.9 9.8 13.2 19.7))

(define coeffs (linalg/least-squares A y-vec))
(define b (vec/ref coeffs 0))
(define m1 (vec/ref coeffs 1))
(define m2 (vec/ref coeffs 2))

(list 'b b 'm1 m1 'm2 m2)
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; prints the three coefficients -->
[VISUAL: text output, a list (b <val> m1 <val> m2 <val>)]

### Example 8.45: Predict from the multiple regression model

```scheme
(define x1s (list 1 2 3 4 5))
(define x2s (list 2 3 5 7 11))
(define ys (list 3.1 5.9 9.8 13.2 19.7))

(define A
  (matrix/make
    (map (lambda (x1 x2) (list 1 x1 x2))
         x1s x2s)))

(define y-vec (vec/make 3.1 5.9 9.8 13.2 19.7))

(define coeffs (linalg/least-squares A y-vec))
(define b (vec/ref coeffs 0))
(define m1 (vec/ref coeffs 1))
(define m2 (vec/ref coeffs 2))

(define predict
  (lambda (x1 x2)
    (+ b (* m1 x1) (* m2 x2))))

(predict 6 13)
```
<!-- BUILD: runs; prints the predicted y for x1=6, x2=13 -->
